Red Wine Quality Exploratory data analysis

Alen Mrsic

23 April 2018

Introduction into the dataset

Our dataset consists of 13 variables, with 1599 observations. A quality variable is discrete and the others are continuous. Red Wine Quality file includes 11 inputs (objective tests) and 1 output that is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts) and 1 index value, variable X. Each expert graded the wine quality between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).With these project, I want to evaluate which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1,599 observations in the dataset with 11 features on the chemical properties of the wine. Chemical properties are: fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and one sensorial feature quality. Most wines have average quality - 1319 (scores between 5 and 6).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest is quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I think that residual sugar and alcohol will contribute most to find out what makes a wine quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created variable quality.class which is divided into three categories: Bad (4-5), Average (5-6), Excellent(7-8).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

There are a few outliers in the plots for fixed acidity, residual sugar, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide so I omit 1% of wines with the highest values. Citric acid has 132 values that were zero, so I checked if that will affect quality variable. I removed all values where citric.acid is zero and compare two data set and we can see that distribution is almost unaffected. Total sulfur dioxide was log transformed and after that, as a result, we got normal distribution

Bivariate Plots Section

Ggpairs plot shows relationship correlations between two variables. In the calculation, I excluded variables X and quality.class. From plot we can see some positive relationship between: fixed acidity and density (r = 0.668), fixed acidity and citric acid (r = 0.672), quality and alcohol (r = 0.476). Also some strong negative relationship between: fixed acidity and pH (r = -0.683), citric acid and pH (r = -0.542 ), alcohol and density (r = -0.496)

We observed the best quality correlation its with alcohol and the best alcohol correlation its with density. The best density correlation being the fixed acidity (quality->alcohol->density->fixed acidity).

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  winedf$quality and winedf$alcohol
## t = 21.639, df = 1597, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4373540 0.5132081
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4761663

A graph shows a positive relationship between alcohol and quality level with a correlation coefficient of 0.476. We can notice that bad and average wines have alcohol percent concentrated around 10. Excellent wines have alcohol percent concentrated near 11.6.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

A quality variable is most positively correlated with alcohol (r = 0.476) and the best alcohol correlation its with density (r =-0.496). The best density correlation being the fixed acidity (r = 0.668). A quality variable is also negatively correlated with volatile acidity (r = -0.391).

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I observed some positive relationship between fixed acidity and density (r = 0.668),fixed acidity and citric acid (r = 0.672) and quality and alcohol (r = 0.476). Also some stronge negative relationship between fixed acidity and pH (r = -0.683),citric acid and pH (r = -0.542 ) and alcohol and density (r = -0.496). These are some of the strongest relationship.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is between fixed acidity and citric acid (r = 0.672) A quality variable is most positively correlated with alcohol (r = 0.476), and it is also negatively correlated with volatile acidity (r = -0.391)

Multivariate Plots Section

The densities of excellent wines are concentrated between 0.995 and 0.997 with average higher alcohol level, for average wines between 0.995 and 0.999 with average lower level than excellent wines. Bad wines densities are concentrated between 0.994 and 0.997 with the lowest alcohol level in average.

The distribution of bad and average quality wines seem to be concentrated at fixed acidity values that are between 6 and 9 with a peak around 7. Also, that wines have bigger density than excellent wines.

## winedf$quality.class: Bad
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2300  0.5650  0.6800  0.7242  0.8825  1.5800 
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## winedf$quality.class: Average
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1600  0.4100  0.5400  0.5386  0.6400  1.3300 
## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## winedf$quality.class: Excellent
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1200  0.3000  0.3700  0.4055  0.4900  0.9150

High volatile acidity and lower citric acid tend to be bad and average wines. Excellent wines have lowest median volatile acidity (0.37) with a higher amount of citric acid (concentrated between 0.3 and 0.6).

High percent alcohol content and low volatile acidity tend to be rated as excellent quality wine. We can see many populations between 0.4 and 0.7 volatile acidity for the average wines with a low percentage of alcohol.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

We explored the relationships between quality, density, alcohol, fixed acidity and citric acid. For example, the densities of excellent wines are concentrated between 0.995 and 0.997 with average higher alcohol level. High alcohol content, low volatile acidity, higher citric acid they all made for a good wine.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

High-quality wines show a balance between fixed acidity and density. A low volatile acidity and high alcohol content rating appeared to be a requirement in order for a wine to be excellent.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The distribution of wine quality is normally distributed. Values are between 3 and 8 and concentrated around 5 and 6. Interesting is that theres no score 1,2,9,10. Also, its interesting that we have more excellent than bad wines.

Plot Two

Description Two

As the correlations between wine quality and alcohol are the strongest, so this plot is interesting because it shows that excellent wines have a higher median of alcohol percentage by volume.

Plot Three

Description Three

Its an interesting plot because it shows that a low volatile acidity and high alcohol percentage appeared to be a requirement for excellent wine.

Reflection

Red wine dataset from 2009. contains 1599 observation and 13 variables. In the beginning, I started with some descriptive statistics and analyzed interesting variables one by one. I added variable quality.class (quality classification) where I classified quality scores: Bad (3-4), Average (5-6), Excellent (7-8).

In bivariate Plots Section, in the beginning, I created ggpairs plot which gave me bigger picture how two variables are correlated with each other. From the plot, I saw some strong positive and negative relationship. In a multivariate analysis, I explored the relationships between quality, density, alcohol, fixed acidity and citric acid. I found out that excellent wines have a higher median of alcohol percentage by volume. Also quality and alcohol have the strongest correlation. Alcohol content appeared to be the number one factor in determining an excellent wine.

Because our dataset is relatively small with few bad and excellent wines, with more data and more variables we could improve the quality of our analysis.
